introduction: >
  - The School 21 methodology can lead to high eduse caseational results only if peer-to-peer assessment is done as responsibly as possible. Please read the instruse casetions carefully before starting the check.

   - Be friendly and polite. Be respectful of the other person and the work they have done. Be construse casetive when giving feedback.

   - When reviewing the work, notice for yourself any incorrect or possibly controversial moments. Discuss them with the author of the solution.

   - Try to be open to a different opinion or way of interpreting the task. It is possible that both your approach and the approach of another may be correct.    

   - If you haven't finished the project yourself, be sure to read it completely before reviewing it.

guidelines: >
  - Evaluate only the files that are in the GIT repository of the student or group.

  -	Start reviewing a group project only when all team members are present.

  -	Use the special flags in the end of the checklist, for example, "EMPTY_WORK", if the repository does not contain the student's (or group's) work in the src directory of the develop branch, or "CHEAT" in the case of plagiarism or if the student (or anyone from the group being reviewed) cannot explain their decision at any time during the review. Also, the "CHEAT" flag is applicable if the following two points are not fulfilled. If one of the flags at the end of the checklist applies, the project will be considered a failure. However, except for a case of cheating, you are encouraged to continue reviewing the project and try to work with another student to figure out the problem that led to the failed solution.  

  -	Doublecheck that the GIT repository is the one corresponding to the student or the group. 

  -	Meticulously check that nothing malicious has been used to mislead you.

  -	In controversial cases, keep in mind that the checklist only defines the general order of the review. The final decision remains with the reviewer.

