sections:
  - kind: "1"
    name: Main part
    description: ""
    questions:
      - name: Exercise 00 — Identification of Requirement Types
        description: |-
          Groups of requirements (by their types) that need to be tracked are written out and requirement attributes are defined for application for Task 1.
          - Types of requirements are defined.
            - Four types of requirements are selected:
              - Business requirements: product goals, objectives, business rules;
              - User (stakeholder) requirements: UC, US, business process diagrams and descriptions, DB schemas, etc.
              - Functional system requirements (system specifications, interfaces);
              - Non-functional system requirements (quality attributes).
            - Each type of requirements is assigned a three-letter identifier.
          - The requirements attributes defined for each type are.
            - State:
              - Date, time of creation;
              - Date, time when the requirement was transferred to its current state;
              - Status of the requirement;
              - Priority of the requirement;
              - Product version in which the requirement is contained;
              - Patch (Sprint, Release) in which the requirement is included.
            - Description and Rationale:
              - A brief title of the requirement (no more than 50 characters);
              - Description of the requirement (no more than 150 characters);
              - Placement of the requirement materials (description, diagram, other) — reference;
              - Method of verification or acceptance criterion;
              - Source of requirement, superior requirement (except business requirements);
              - Relationship of the requirement.
            - Responsible Persons:
              - Current executor;
              - The decision maker of the requirement;
              - The author of the requirement (who registered).
          - The statuses of the requirements are defined as:
            - New;
            - Under analysis;
            - In development;
            - In testing;
            - Included in Patch;
            - Rejected;
            - Postponed;
            - Completed.
          - A personalized instance of WEEEK (or another service) has been deployed ()
          - The requirements listed above are created in WEEEK (or another service).
          - Scaning of WEEEK (or another service) is performed and the scan is placed in the response.

        rating: "6"

      - name: Exercise 01 — Creation of Requirements and Registration
        description: |-
          The requirements are described in terms of the highlighted record of Тask 1. Registered in WEEEK (or another service) personal instance and specified parameters.
          - Stakeholder requirements are described in terms of user stories and registered in service. The one highlighted by the cursor is decomposed:
            - The manager informs the client about the service appointment;
            - The client receiving the information about the service appointment;
            - Interactions on the information channels;
            - Creation of the information schedule.
          - System functionality requirements are described and recorded in service to meet business requirements for
            - Setting up a schedule;
            - Automatically sending reminders.
          - System interface requirements are described and registered in service to meet business requirements for:
            - Set up a schedule;
            - Automatically send reminders.
          - Requirements are prioritized.
          - Specify dependencies between different types of requirements in the Source attribute in service.
          - Horizontal relationships between requirements are specified in the Relationships attribute in service.
          - The service is scanned and placed in the response.

        rating: "6"

      - name: Exercise 02 — Creating a Positive Test Case
        description: |-
          For Task 1, positive test cases are developed for UC02.
          - The following are specified for test cases:
            - Alphanumeric identifier;
            - Test short name;
            - Priority;
            - Precondition (if necessary)
            - Select a manager person from the Employee entity who has the role of Manager in the Employee Role entity;
            - Execution steps (instructions, simple and unambiguous, specifying the correct values of the required parameters when executed);
            - Expected Result (ER);
            - Postconditions (how to restore the state before the check);
            - Actual Result (ER);
            - Each case corresponds to the principle of repeatability (F.I. Repeatable S.T.);
            - Each case corresponds to the principle of Atomicity/Independence (F.Independent.S.T.);
            - Presented in tabular form.

        rating: "6"

      - name: Exercise 03 — Creating a Negative Test Case
        description: |-
          For Task 1, negative test cases for UC02 are developed.
          - The following is specified for each test case
            - Alphanumeric identifier;
            - Test short name;
            - Priority;
            - Precondition, if necessary;
            - Select a manager person from the Employee entity who has the role of Manager in the Employee Role entity;
            - Execution steps (instructions, simple and unambiguous, specifying the correct values of the required parameters when executed);
            - Expected Result (ER);
            - Postconditions (how to restore the state before the check);
            - Actual Result (ER);
            - Each case corresponds to the principle of Repeatability (F.I. Repeatable S.T.);
            - Each case corresponds to the principle of Atomicity/Independence (F.Independent.S.T);
            - Presented in tabular form.


        rating: "6"

      - name: Exercise 04 — Result Evaluation
        description: |-
          For Task 1 UC02, the results of the positive test case are discussed.
          - The result of the test case is determined and an issue report is created if necessary.
          - After completing steps 1, 2:
            - The system reports that the selected slot is booked in the system by the client. However, when contacting the client, the client denies having booked this slot.
            - The system reports that the selected slot is not booked in the system by the client.
          - After completing steps 1-5:
            - The system assigns the slot to the master, the slot does not appear in the list of free slots during further work;
            - the system does not assign the slot to a Master. This slot can also be selected from the list of free slots for further work.
          - In case of a negative test case result:
            - An error report is created. The following is described:
              - Defect identifier (alphanumeric);
              - Brief description (one sentence, "what, where, when?");
              - *Prerequisite (if necessary);
              - Steps to reproduce the defect (not necessarily the same as the text case steps);
              - Expected Result (ER): the positive result of the test case that was expected after testing;
              - Actual Result (AR): the result obtained from the execution, highlighting what makes it different from the ER;
              - *Postconditions (how to restore the state before testing);
              - *Environment (description of the environment: operating system, browser, screen resolution, etc.);
              - Priority (urgency of fixing the bug);
              - *Importance (criticality to execution);
              - Description;
              - Supporting documentation (screenshots, logs, documents, etc.).
            - The AR column contains a negative result mark and the reported defect identifier.
          - In the case of a positive test case result, the AR column contains a positive case pass mark.

        rating: "6"

